## What happened

**`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in .NET 11.** Apple's security frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) never implemented DSA. Earlier .NET versions included a compatibility shim, but .NET 11 removed it, aligning with Microsoft's progressive deprecation of legacy crypto algorithms. The API was already marked `[Obsolete]` with compiler warnings in prior releases.

Linux and Windows still work because they use OpenSSL and Windows CNG respectively, both of which support DSA.

## How to fix it

Use **BouncyCastle** (`BouncyCastle.Cryptography` on NuGet) for cross-platform DSA signature verification:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the `DSA.Create()` usage with BouncyCastle's platform-independent implementation:

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(
    byte[] data, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)
{
    ISigner signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

If you're loading the key from an existing `DSAParameters` struct, convert it:

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Math;
using System.Security.Cryptography;

public static DsaPublicKeyParameters ToDsaPublicKey(DSAParameters p)
{
    var parameters = new DsaParameters(
        new BigInteger(1, p.P),
        new BigInteger(1, p.Q),
        new BigInteger(1, p.G));
    return new DsaPublicKeyParameters(new BigInteger(1, p.Y), parameters);
}
```

**Long-term**, plan to migrate off DSA entirely — it's a legacy algorithm. ECDSA or Ed25519 are the modern replacements.
